1. Open Hyper-V Manager on your Windows Server machine and create a new virtual machine named 'MyTestVM' with default settings.
==>Open Hyper-V Manager (search for it in the Start menu).
In the right Actions pane, click New → Virtual Machine.
Follow the wizard with default settings:
Name: MyTestVM
Generation: Generation 2 (recommended)
Memory: Default (usually 512 MB or 1 GB)
Network: Not connected yet
Virtual Hard Disk: Create a new one (default size/location)
Installation Options: Leave for later

2. Configure a virtual switch in Hyper-V Manager that allows your virtual machines to access the internet, and attach 'MyTestVM' to this switch.<br><br><em><strong>Hint:</strong> Use the Virtual Switch Manager and select 'External' for internet access.</em>
=>In Hyper-V Manager, click Virtual Switch Manager (right pane).
Select New virtual network switch → External → Create Virtual Switch.
Give it a name (e.g., ExternalSwitch).
Select your physical network adapter that has internet access.
Click Apply / OK.
Right-click MyTestVM → Settings → Network Adapter.
Set Virtual switch to the one you just created (ExternalSwitch).
Click OK.

3. Install a Windows 10 ISO on 'MyTestVM' and ensure it boots successfully to the desktop.
=>Right-click MyTestVM → Settings → SCSI Controller → Hard Drive → Add (if needed) or use the existing one.
Under DVD Drive, click Browse and select your Windows 10 ISO file.
Click OK.
Right-click the VM → Start.
Right-click → Connect to open the VM console.
Complete the Windows 10 installation (choose Custom install, select the virtual disk).
After installation, the VM should boot to the Windows 10 desktop.

4. Take a snapshot (checkpoint) of 'MyTestVM' after installation, then make a change inside the VM (like creating a folder on the desktop), and restore the VM to the checkpoint to verify the change is undone.
=>With the VM running or shut down, right-click MyTestVM → Checkpoint (or Take Checkpoint).
Name it e.g. Post-Install.
Inside the VM: Create a folder on the Desktop named TestFolder.
Shut down the VM if needed.
Right-click MyTestVM → Revert (or Apply Checkpoint).
Start the VM again → verify the TestFolder is gone. The checkpoint worked.

5. Use ChatGPT or Copilot to generate PowerShell commands for creating a new Hyper-V VM with 2GB RAM and a 40GB disk, then run the commands and verify the VM appears in Hyper-V Manager.
=># Create new Hyper-V VM with 2GB RAM and 40GB disk
$VMName = "PowerShellVM"
$RAM = 2GB
$DiskSize = 40GB
$VHDPath = "C:\Hyper-V\Virtual Hard Disks\$VMName.vhdx"  # Change path if needed
$SwitchName = "ExternalSwitch"  # Use the switch you created earlier

# Create directory if it doesn't exist
New-Item -Path "C:\Hyper-V\Virtual Hard Disks" -ItemType Directory -Force

# Create the VM
New-VM -Name $VMName `
       -MemoryStartupBytes $RAM `
       -Generation 2 `
       -NewVHDPath $VHDPath `
       -NewVHDSizeBytes $DiskSize `
       -SwitchName $SwitchName

# Optional: Set processor count and enable dynamic memory
Set-VM -Name $VMName -ProcessorCount 2 -DynamicMemory

# Verify
Get-VM -Name $VMName | Format-List Name, State, MemoryAssigned, ProcessorCount
